sec.p:
Rapid urbanization and industrial expansion have intensified air pollution, posing serious threats to human health and environmental quality1. According to the Air Quality Annual Report of R.O.C. (Taiwan), 2024, the annual average PM2.5 concentration measured by Taiwan’s air quality automated monitoring stations was \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:14.1\pm\:3.5$$\end{document} µg/m³2, frequently exceeding the World Health Organization’s interim air quality target of 10 µg/m³3. This intensification of air pollution poses a serious threat to human health, as research has concluded that long-term (30-year) exposure to PM2.5 is associated with elevated risk of adenocarcinoma lung cancer4. The current air quality monitoring network consists of 80 ground stations (77 main islands and 3 outlying islands) that record hourly measurements of 6 pollutants: PM2.5, particulate matter with an aerodynamic diameter ≤ 10 μm (PM10), sulfur dioxide (SO2), nitrogen dioxide (NO2), carbon monoxide (CO), and ozone (O3). Most monitoring stations are concentrated in urban centers and industrial corridors, leaving some regions without direct measurements5. This spatial imbalance makes it challenging to obtain a comprehensive, real-time understanding of air quality across the entire island.

