				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\:{feature\_total\_importance}_{F}={feature\_importance}_{j}+{\sum\:}_{i=1}^{N}{average\_feature\_importance}_{i}.$$\end{document}

This study employed the CatBoost model to predict the ground-level concentrations of multiple pollutants. Hyperparameter tuning was conducted to optimize model performance within the rolling prediction framework. We performed a grid search over the parameter space, specifically targeting the iterations {700, 1000, 1200, 1400} and learning rates {0.3, 0.4, 0.5}. The optimal hyperparameter configuration was selected based on the lowest aggregate Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) across all six pollutants derived from the comprehensive 6-month rolling validation period (July 1 to December 31, 2023). Balancing accuracy with computational efficiency, we set the number of iterations to 1400 and the learning rate to 0.4. The multiple root mean square error (MultiRMSE) was chosen as the loss function. As a common metric in multi-output regression, MultiRMSE effectively measures the model’s overall prediction error across various response variables. This makes it particularly suitable for tasks requiring the prediction of multiple dimensions.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$MultiRMSE = \sqrt {\frac{{\sum \: _{{i = 1}}^{N} \sum \: _{{d = 1}}^{{dim}} (a_{{i,d}} - t_{{i,d}} )^{2} w_{i} }}{{\sum \: _{{i = 1}}^{N} w_{i} }}} ,$$\end{document}

